__fi__ By 2050 there will be 9 billion of us , and according to the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization , we will need to produce twice as much food in 2050 than we do today .
__fi__ So , we will have less phosphorus , but we &apos;ll need to produce more food .
__fi__ What should we do ?
__fi__ It truly is a paradoxical situation .
__fi__ Do we have a solution , or an alternative which will allow us to optimize phosphorus use ?
__fi__ Remember that 80 percent is destined to be lost .
__fi__ The solution I &apos;m offering today is one that has existed for a very long time , even before plants existed on Earth , and it &apos;s a microscopic mushroom that is very mysterious , very simple , and yet also extremely complex .
__fi__ I &apos;ve been fascinated by this little mushroom for over 16 years now .
__fi__ It has led me to further my research and to use it as a model for my laboratory research .
__fi__ This mushroom exists in symbiosis with the roots .
__fi__ By symbiosis , I mean a bidirectional and mutually beneficial association which is also called mycorrhiza .
__fi__ This slide illustrates the elements of a mycorrhiza .
__fi__ You ’ re looking at the root of wheat , one of the world ’ s most important plants .
__fi__ Normally , a root will find phosphorus all by itself .
__fi__ It will go in search of phosphorus , but only within the one millimeter which surrounds it .
__fi__ Beyond one millimeter , the root is ineffective .
__fi__ It cannot go further in its search for phosphorus .
__fi__ Now , imagine this tiny , microscopic mushroom .
__fi__ It grows much faster , and is much better designed to seek out phosphorus .
__fi__ It can go beyond the root ’ s one-millimeter scope to seek out phosphorus .
__fi__ I haven ’ t invented anything at all ; it &apos;s a biotechnology that has existed for 450 million years .
__fi__ And over time , this mushroom has evolved and adapted to seek out even the tiniest trace of phosphorus , and to put it to use , to make it available to the plant .
__fi__ What you ’ re seeing here , in the real world , is a carrot root , and the mushroom with its very fine filaments .
__fi__ Looking closer , we can see that this mushroom is very gentle in its penetration .
__fi__ It will proliferate between the root &apos;s cells , eventually penetrating a cell and starting to form a typical arbuscular structure , which will considerably increase the exchange interface between the plant and the mushroom .
__fi__ And it is through this structure that mutual exchanges will occur .
__fi__ It ’ s a win-win trade : I give you phosphorus , and you feed me .
__fi__ True symbiosis .
__fi__ Now let &apos;s add a mycorrhiza plant into the diagram I used earlier .
__fi__ And instead of using a 100 percent dose , I ’ m going to reduce it to 25 percent .
__fi__ You ’ ll see that of this 25 percent , most will benefit the plant , more than 90 percent .
__fi__ A very small amount of phosphorus will remain in the soil .
__fi__ That &apos;s completely natural .
__fi__ What &apos;s more is that in certain cases , we don &apos;t even need to add phosphorus .
__fi__ If you recall the graphs I showed you earlier , 85 percent of phosphorus is lost in the soil , and the plants are unable to access it .
__fi__ Even though it is present in the soil , it is in insoluble form .
__fi__ The plant is only able to seek out soluble forms .
__fi__ The mushroom is capable of dissolving this insoluble form and making it available for the plant to use .
__fi__ To further support my argument , here is a picture that speaks for itself .
__fi__ These are trials in a field of sorghum .
__fi__ On the left side , you see the yield produced using conventional agriculture , with a 100 percent phosphorus dose .
__fi__ On the other side , the dose was reduced to 50 percent , and just look at the yield .
__fi__ With only a half-dose , we achieved a better yield .
__fi__ This is to show you that this method works .
__fi__ And in some cases , in Cuba , Mexico and India , the dose can be reduced to 25 percent , and in several other cases , there &apos;s no need to add any phosphorus at all , because the mushrooms are so well adapted to finding phosphorus and drawing it from the soil .
