__fi__ I &apos;m a writer and a journalist , and I &apos;m also an insanely curious person , so in 22 years as a journalist , I &apos;ve learned how to do a lot of new things .
__fi__ And three years ago , one of the things I learned how to do was to become invisible .
__fi__ I became one of the working homeless .
__fi__ I quit my job as a newspaper editor after my father died in February of that same year , and decided to travel .
__fi__ His death hit me pretty hard .
__fi__ And there were a lot of things that I wanted to feel and deal with while I was doing that .
__fi__ I &apos;ve camped my whole life . And I decided that living in a van for a year to do this would be like one long camping trip .
__fi__ So I packed my cat , my Rottweiler and my camping gear into a 1975 Chevy van , and drove off into the sunset , having fully failed to realize three critical things .
__fi__ One : that society equates living in a permanent structure , even a shack , with having value as a person .
__fi__ Two : I failed to realize how quickly the negative perceptions of other people can impact our reality , if we let it .
__fi__ Three : I failed to realize that homelessness is an attitude , not a lifestyle .
__fi__ At first , living in the van was great .
__fi__ I showered in campgrounds . I ate out regularly .
__fi__ And I had time to relax and to grieve .
__fi__ But then the anger and the depression about my father &apos;s death set in .
__fi__ My freelance job ended . And I had to get a full-time job to pay the bills .
__fi__ What had been a really mild spring turned into a miserably hot summer .
__fi__ And it became impossible to park anywhere — ( Laughs ) — without being very obvious that I had a cat and a dog with me , and it was really hot .
__fi__ The cat came and went through an open window in the van .
__fi__ The doggy went into doggy day care .
__fi__ And I sweated .
__fi__ Whenever I could , I used employee showers in office buildings and truck stops .
__fi__ Or I washed up in public rest rooms .
__fi__ Nighttime temperatures in the van rarely dropped below 80 degrees Fahrenheit , making it difficult or impossible to sleep .
__fi__ Food rotted in the heat .
__fi__ Ice in my ice chest melted within hours , and it was pretty miserable .
__fi__ I couldn &apos;t afford to find an apartment , or couldn &apos;t afford an apartment that would allow me to have the Rottweiler and the cat .
__fi__ And I refused to give them up , so I stayed in the van .
__fi__ And when the heat made me too sick to walk the 50 feet to the public restroom outside my van at night , I used a bucket and a trash bag as a toilet .
__fi__ When winter weather set in , the temperatures dropped below freezing . And they stayed there .
__fi__ And I faced a whole new set of challenges .
__fi__ I parked a different place every night so I would avoid being noticed and hassled by the police .
__fi__ I didn &apos;t always succeed .
__fi__ But I felt out of control of my life .
__fi__ And I don &apos;t know when or how it happened , but the speed at which I went from being a talented writer and journalist to being a homeless woman , living in a van , took my breath away .
__fi__ I hadn &apos;t changed . My I.Q. hadn &apos;t dropped .
