__fi__ On January 4 , 1934 , a young man delivered a report to the United States Congress that 80 years on , still shapes the lives of everyone in this room today , still shapes the lives of everyone on this planet .
__fi__ That young man wasn &apos;t a politician , he wasn &apos;t a businessman , a civil rights activist or a faith leader .
__fi__ He was that most unlikely of heroes , an economist .
__fi__ His name was Simon Kuznets and the report that he delivered was called &quot; National Income , 1929-1932 . &quot;
__fi__ Now , you might think this is a rather dry and dull report .
__fi__ And you &apos;re absolutely right .
__fi__ It &apos;s dry as a bone .
__fi__ But this report is the foundation of how , today , we judge the success of countries : what we know best as Gross Domestic Product , GDP .
__fi__ GDP has defined and shaped our lives for the last 80 years .
__fi__ And today I want to talk about a different way to measure the success of countries , a different way to define and shape our lives for the next 80 years .
__fi__ But first , we have to understand how GDP came to dominate our lives .
__fi__ Kuznets &apos; report was delivered at a moment of crisis .
__fi__ The U.S. economy was plummeting into the Great Depression and policy makers were struggling to respond .
__fi__ Struggling because they didn &apos;t know what was going on .
__fi__ They didn &apos;t have data and statistics .
__fi__ So what Kuznet &apos;s report gave them was reliable data on what the U.S. economy was producing , updated year by year .
__fi__ And armed with this information , policy makers were , eventually , able to find a way out of the slump .
__fi__ And because Kuznets &apos; invention was found to be so useful , it spread around the world .
__fi__ And now today , every country produces GDP statistics .
__fi__ But , in that first report , Kuznets himself delivered a warning .
__fi__ It &apos;s in the introductory chapter .
__fi__ On page seven he says , &quot; &quot; The welfare of a nation can , therefore , scarcely be inferred from a measurement of national income as defined above . &quot; &quot; It &apos;s not the greatest sound bite in the world , and it &apos;s dressed up in the cautious language of the economist .
__fi__ But his message was clear : GDP is a tool to help us measure economic performance .
__fi__ It &apos;s not a measure of our well-being .
__fi__ And it shouldn &apos;t be a guide to all decision making .
__fi__ But we have ignored Kuznets &apos; warning .
__fi__ We live in a world where GDP is the benchmark of success in a global economy .
__fi__ Our politicians boast when GDP goes up .
__fi__ Markets move and trillions of dollars of capital move around the world based on which countries are going up and which countries are going down , all measured in GDP .
__fi__ Our societies have become engines to create more GDP .
__fi__ But we know that GDP is flawed .
__fi__ It ignores the environment .
__fi__ It counts bombs and prisons as progress .
__fi__ It can &apos;t count happiness or community .
__fi__ And it has nothing to say about fairness or justice .
__fi__ Is it any surprise that our world , marching to the drumbeat of GDP , is teetering on the brink of environmental disaster and filled with anger and conflict ?
__fi__ We need a better way to measure our societies , a measure based on the real things that matter to real people .
__fi__ Do I have enough to eat ?
__fi__ Can I read and write ?
__fi__ Am I safe ?
__fi__ Do I have rights ?
__fi__ Do I live in a society where I &apos;m not discriminated against ?
__fi__ Is my future and the future of my children prevented from environmental destruction ?
__fi__ These are questions that GDP does not and cannot answer .
__fi__ There have , of course , been efforts in the past to move beyond GDP .
__fi__ But I believe that we &apos;re living in a moment when we are ready for a measurement revolution .
__fi__ We &apos;re ready because we &apos;ve seen , in the financial crisis of 2008 , how our fetish for economic growth led us so far astray .
__fi__ We &apos;ve seen , in the Arab Spring , how countries like Tunisia were supposedly economic superstars , but they were societies that were seething with discontentment .
__fi__ We &apos;re ready , because today we have the technology to gather and analyze data in ways that would have been unimaginable to Kuznets .
__fi__ Today , I &apos;d like to introduce you to the Social Progress Index .
__fi__ It &apos;s a measure of the well-being of society , completely separate from GDP .
__fi__ It &apos;s a whole new way of looking at the world .
__fi__ The Social Progress Index begins by defining what it means to be a good society based around three dimensions .
__fi__ The first is , does everyone have the basic needs for survival : food , water , shelter , safety ?
__fi__ Secondly , does everyone have access to the building blocks to improve their lives : education , information , health and sustainable environment ?
__fi__ And then third , does every individual have access to a chance to pursue their goals and dreams and ambitions free from obstacles ?
__fi__ Do they have rights , freedom of choice , freedom from discrimination and access to the the world &apos;s most advanced knowledge ?
__fi__ Together , these 12 components form the Social Progress framework .
__fi__ And for each of these 12 components , we have indicators to measure how countries are performing .
__fi__ Not indicators of effort or intention , but real achievement .
__fi__ We don &apos;t measure how much a country spends on healthcare , we measure the length and quality of people &apos;s lives .
__fi__ We don &apos;t measure whether governments pass laws against discrimination , we measure whether people experience discrimination .
