__fi__ Today , I &apos;m going to take you around the world in 18 minutes .
__fi__ My base of operations is in the U.S. , but let &apos;s start at the other end of the map , in Kyoto , Japan , where I was living with a Japanese family while I was doing part of my dissertational research 15 years ago .
__fi__ I knew even then that I would encounter cultural differences and misunderstandings , but they popped up when I least expected it .
__fi__ On my first day , I went to a restaurant , and I ordered a cup of green tea with sugar .
__fi__ After a pause , the waiter said , &quot; One does not put sugar in green tea . &quot;
__fi__ &quot; &quot; I know , &quot; &quot; I said . &quot; &quot; I &apos;m aware of this custom .
__fi__ But I really like my tea sweet . &quot; &quot; In response , he gave me an even more courteous version of the same explanation .
__fi__ &quot; &quot; One does not put sugar in green tea . &quot; &quot; &quot; &quot; I understand , &quot; &quot; I said , &quot; &quot; that the Japanese do not put sugar in their green tea , but I &apos;d like to put some sugar in my green tea . &quot; &quot; ( Laughter ) Surprised by my insistence , the waiter took up the issue with the manager .
__fi__ Pretty soon , a lengthy discussion ensued , and finally the manager came over to me and said , &quot; I am very sorry . We do not have sugar . &quot;
__fi__ ( Laughter ) Well , since I couldn &apos;t have my tea the way I wanted it , I ordered a cup of coffee , which the waiter brought over promptly .
__fi__ Resting on the saucer were two packets of sugar .
__fi__ My failure to procure myself a cup of sweet , green tea was not due to a simple misunderstanding .
__fi__ This was due to a fundamental difference in our ideas about choice .
__fi__ From my American perspective , when a paying customer makes a reasonable request based on her preferences , she has every right to have that request met .
__fi__ The American way , to quote Burger King , is to &quot; &quot; have it your way , &quot; &quot; because , as Starbucks says , &quot; happiness is in your choices . &quot;
__fi__ ( Laughter ) But from the Japanese perspective , it &apos;s their duty to protect those who don &apos;t know any better — ( Laughter ) in this case , the ignorant gaijin — from making the wrong choice .
__fi__ Let &apos;s face it : the way I wanted my tea was inappropriate according to cultural standards , and they were doing their best to help me save face .
__fi__ Americans tend to believe that they &apos;ve reached some sort of pinnacle in the way they practice choice .
__fi__ They think that choice , as seen through the American lens best fulfills an innate and universal desire for choice in all humans .
__fi__ Unfortunately , these beliefs are based on assumptions that don &apos;t always hold true in many countries , in many cultures .
__fi__ At times they don &apos;t even hold true at America &apos;s own borders .
__fi__ I &apos;d like to discuss some of these assumptions and the problems associated with them .
__fi__ As I do so , I hope you &apos;ll start thinking about some of your own assumptions and how they were shaped by your backgrounds .
__fi__ First assumption : if a choice affects you , then you should be the one to make it .
__fi__ This is the only way to ensure that your preferences and interests will be most fully accounted for .
__fi__ It is essential for success .
__fi__ In America , the primary locus of choice is the individual .
__fi__ People must choose for themselves , sometimes sticking to their guns , regardless of what other people want or recommend .
__fi__ It &apos;s called &quot; &quot; being true to yourself . &quot; &quot; But do all individuals benefit from taking such an approach to choice ?
__fi__ Mark Lepper and I did a series of studies in which we sought the answer to this very question .
__fi__ In one study , which we ran in Japantown , San Francisco , we brought seven- to nine-year-old Anglo- and Asian-American children into the laboratory , and we divided them up into three groups .
__fi__ The first group came in , and they were greeted by Miss Smith , who showed them six big piles of anagram puzzles .
__fi__ The kids got to choose which pile of anagrams they would like to do , and they even got to choose which marker they would write their answers with .
__fi__ When the second group of children came in , they were brought to the same room , shown the same anagrams , but this time Miss Smith told them which anagrams to do and which markers to write their answers with .
__fi__ Now when the third group came in , they were told that their anagrams and their markers had been chosen by their mothers .
__fi__ ( Laughter ) In reality , the kids who were told what to do , whether by Miss Smith or their mothers , were actually given the very same activity , which their counterparts in the first group had freely chosen .
__fi__ With this procedure , we were able to ensure that the kids across the three groups all did the same activity , making it easier for us to compare performance .
__fi__ Such small differences in the way we administered the activity yielded striking differences in how well they performed .
__fi__ Anglo-Americans , they did two and a half times more anagrams when they got to choose them , as compared to when it was chosen for them by Miss Smith or their mothers .
__fi__ It didn &apos;t matter who did the choosing , if the task was dictated by another , their performance suffered .
__fi__ In fact , some of the kids were visibly embarrassed when they were told that their mothers had been consulted .
__fi__ ( Laughter ) One girl named Mary said , &quot; You asked my mother ? &quot; ( Laughter )
__fi__ In contrast , Asian-American children performed best when they believed their mothers had made the choice , second best when they chose for themselves , and least well when it had been chosen by Miss Smith .
__fi__ A girl named Natsumi even approached Miss Smith as she was leaving the room and tugged on her skirt and asked , &quot; &quot; Could you please tell my mommy I did it just like she said ? &quot; &quot; The first-generation children were strongly influenced by their immigrant parents &apos; approach to choice .
__fi__ For them , choice was not just a way of defining and asserting their individuality , but a way to create community and harmony by deferring to the choices of people whom they trusted and respected .
__fi__ If they had a concept of being true to one &apos;s self , then that self , most likely , &#91; was &#93; composed , not of an individual , but of a collective .
__fi__ Success was just as much about pleasing key figures as it was about satisfying one &apos;s own preferences .
__fi__ Or , you could say that the individual &apos;s preferences were shaped by the preferences of specific others .
__fi__ The assumption then that we do best when the individual self chooses only holds when that self is clearly divided from others .
__fi__ When , in contrast , two or more individuals see their choices and their outcomes as intimately connected , then they may amplify one another &apos;s success by turning choosing into a collective act .
__fi__ To insist that they choose independently might actually compromise both their performance and their relationships .
__fi__ Yet that is exactly what the American paradigm demands .
__fi__ It leaves little room for interdependence or an acknowledgment of individual fallibility .
__fi__ It requires that everyone treat choice as a private and self-defining act .
__fi__ People that have grown up in such a paradigm might find it motivating , but it is a mistake to assume that everyone thrives under the pressure of choosing alone .
__fi__ The second assumption which informs the American view of choice goes something like this .
__fi__ The more choices you have , the more likely you are to make the best choice .
__fi__ So bring it on , Walmart , with 100,000 different products , and Amazon , with 27 million books and Match.com with — what is it ? — 15 million date possibilities now .
__fi__ You will surely find the perfect match .
__fi__ Let &apos;s test this assumption by heading over to Eastern Europe .
__fi__ Here , I interviewed people who were residents of formerly communist countries , who had all faced the challenge of transitioning to a more democratic and capitalistic society .
__fi__ One of the most interesting revelations came not from an answer to a question , but from a simple gesture of hospitality .
__fi__ When the participants arrived for their interview , I offered them a set of drinks : Coke , Diet Coke , Sprite — seven , to be exact .
__fi__ During the very first session , which was run in Russia , one of the participants made a comment that really caught me off guard .
__fi__ &quot; &quot; Oh , but it doesn &apos;t matter .
__fi__ It &apos;s all just soda . That &apos;s just one choice . &quot; &quot; ( Murmuring ) I was so struck by this comment that from then on , I started to offer all the participants those seven sodas , and I asked them , &quot; &quot; How many choices are these ? &quot; &quot; Again and again , they perceived these seven different sodas , not as seven choices , but as one choice : soda or no soda .
__fi__ When I put out juice and water in addition to these seven sodas , now they perceived it as only three choices — juice , water and soda .
__fi__ Compare this to the die-hard devotion of many Americans , not just to a particular flavor of soda , but to a particular brand .
__fi__ You know , research shows repeatedly that we can &apos;t actually tell the difference between Coke and Pepsi .
__fi__ Of course , you and I know that Coke is the better choice .
__fi__ ( Laughter ) For modern Americans who are exposed to more options and more ads associated with options than anyone else in the world , choice is just as much about who they are as it is about what the product is .
__fi__ Combine this with the assumption that more choices are always better , and you have a group of people for whom every little difference matters and so every choice matters .
__fi__ But for Eastern Europeans , the sudden availability of all these consumer products on the marketplace was a deluge .
__fi__ They were flooded with choice before they could protest that they didn &apos;t know how to swim .
__fi__ When asked , &quot; &quot; What words and images do you associate with choice ? &quot; &quot; Grzegorz from Warsaw said , &quot; &quot; Ah , for me it is fear .
__fi__ There are some dilemmas you see .
__fi__ I am used to no choice . &quot; &quot; Bohdan from Kiev said , in response to how he felt about the new consumer marketplace , &quot; &quot; It is too much .
__fi__ We do not need everything that is there . &quot; &quot; A sociologist from the Warsaw Survey Agency explained , &quot; &quot; The older generation jumped from nothing to choice all around them .
__fi__ They were never given a chance to learn how to react . &quot; &quot; And Tomasz , a young Polish man said , &quot; &quot; I don &apos;t need twenty kinds of chewing gum .
__fi__ I don &apos;t mean to say that I want no choice , but many of these choices are quite artificial . &quot; &quot; In reality , many choices are between things that are not that much different .
__fi__ The value of choice depends on our ability to perceive differences between the options .
__fi__ Americans train their whole lives to play &quot; &quot; spot the difference . &quot; &quot; They practice this from such an early age that they &apos;ve come to believe that everyone must be born with this ability .
__fi__ In fact , though all humans share a basic need and desire for choice , we don &apos;t all see choice in the same places or to the same extent .
__fi__ When someone can &apos;t see how one choice is unlike another , or when there are too many choices to compare and contrast , the process of choosing can be confusing and frustrating .
__fi__ Instead of making better choices , we become overwhelmed by choice , sometimes even afraid of it .
__fi__ Choice no longer offers opportunities , but imposes constraints .
__fi__ It &apos;s not a marker of liberation , but of suffocation by meaningless minutiae .
__fi__ In other words , choice can develop into the very opposite of everything it represents in America when it is thrust upon those who are insufficiently prepared for it .
__fi__ But it is not only other people in other places that are feeling the pressure of ever-increasing choice .
__fi__ Americans themselves are discovering that unlimited choice seems more attractive in theory than in practice .
__fi__ We all have physical , mental and emotional ( Laughter ) limitations that make it impossible for us to process every single choice we encounter , even in the grocery store , let alone over the course of our entire lives .
__fi__ A number of my studies have shown that when you give people 10 or more options when they &apos;re making a choice , they make poorer decisions , whether it be health care , investment , other critical areas .
__fi__ Yet still , many of us believe that we should make all our own choices and seek out even more of them .
__fi__ This brings me to the third , and perhaps most problematic , assumption : &quot; &quot; You must never say no to choice . &quot; &quot; To examine this , let &apos;s go back to the U.S.
__fi__ and then hop across the pond to France .
__fi__ Right outside Chicago , a young couple , Susan and Daniel Mitchell , were about to have their first baby .
__fi__ They &apos;d already picked out a name for her , Barbara , after her grandmother .
__fi__ One night , when Susan was seven months pregnant , she started to experience contractions and was rushed to the emergency room .
__fi__ The baby was delivered through a C-section , but Barbara suffered cerebral anoxia , a loss of oxygen to the brain .
__fi__ Unable to breathe on her own , she was put on a ventilator .
__fi__ Two days later , the doctors gave the Mitchells a choice : They could either remove Barbara off the life support , in which case she would die within a matter of hours , or they could keep her on life support , in which case she might still die within a matter of days .
__fi__ If she survived , she would remain in a permanent vegetative state , never able to walk , talk or interact with others .
__fi__ What do they do ?
__fi__ What do any parent do ?
__fi__ In a study I conducted with Simona Botti and Kristina Orfali , American and French parents were interviewed .
__fi__ They had all suffered the same tragedy .
__fi__ In all cases , the life support was removed , and the infants had died .
__fi__ But there was a big difference .
__fi__ In France , the doctors decided whether and when the life support would be removed , while in the United States , the final decision rested with the parents .
__fi__ We wondered : does this have an effect on how the parents cope with the loss of their loved one ?
__fi__ We found that it did .
__fi__ Even up to a year later , American parents were more likely to express negative emotions , as compared to their French counterparts .
__fi__ French parents were more likely to say things like , &quot; &quot; Noah was here for so little time , but he taught us so much .
__fi__ He gave us a new perspective on life . &quot; &quot; American parents were more likely to say things like , &quot; What if ? What if ? &quot;
__fi__ Another parent complained , &quot; &quot; I feel as if they purposefully tortured me .
__fi__ How did they get me to do that ? &quot; &quot; And another parent said , &quot; &quot; I feel as if I &apos;ve played a role in an execution . &quot; &quot; But when the American parents were asked if they would rather have had the doctors make the decision , they all said , &quot; &quot; No . &quot; &quot; They could not imagine turning that choice over to another , even though having made that choice made them feel trapped , guilty , angry .
__fi__ In a number of cases they were even clinically depressed .
__fi__ These parents could not contemplate giving up the choice , because to do so would have gone contrary to everything they had been taught and everything they had come to believe about the power and purpose of choice .
__fi__ In her essay , &quot; &quot; The White Album , &quot; &quot; Joan Didion writes , &quot; &quot; We tell ourselves stories in order to live .
__fi__ We interpret what we see , select the most workable of the multiple choices .
