__fi__ Seventy-thousand years ago , our ancestors were insignificant animals .
__fi__ The most important thing to know about prehistoric humans is that they were unimportant .
__fi__ Their impact on the world was not much greater than that of jellyfish or fireflies or woodpeckers .
__fi__ Today , in contrast , we control this planet .
__fi__ And the question is : How did we come from there to here ?
__fi__ How did we turn ourselves from insignificant apes , minding their own business in a corner of Africa , into the rulers of planet Earth ?
__fi__ Usually , we look for the difference between us and all the other animals on the individual level .
__fi__ We want to believe — I want to believe — that there is something special about me , about my body , about my brain , that makes me so superior to a dog or a pig , or a chimpanzee .
__fi__ But the truth is that , on the individual level , I &apos;m embarrassingly similar to a chimpanzee .
__fi__ And if you take me and a chimpanzee and put us together on some lonely island , and we had to struggle for survival to see who survives better , I would definitely place my bet on the chimpanzee , not on myself .
__fi__ And this is not something wrong with me personally .
__fi__ I guess if they took almost any one of you , and placed you alone with a chimpanzee on some island , the chimpanzee would do much better .
__fi__ The real difference between humans and all other animals is not on the individual level ; it &apos;s on the collective level .
__fi__ Humans control the planet because they are the only animals that can cooperate both flexibly and in very large numbers .
__fi__ Now , there are other animals — like the social insects , the bees , the ants — that can cooperate in large numbers , but they don &apos;t do so flexibly .
__fi__ Their cooperation is very rigid .
__fi__ There is basically just one way in which a beehive can function .
__fi__ And if there &apos;s a new opportunity or a new danger , the bees cannot reinvent the social system overnight .
__fi__ They cannot , for example , execute the queen and establish a republic of bees , or a communist dictatorship of worker bees .
__fi__ Other animals , like the social mammals — the wolves , the elephants , the dolphins , the chimpanzees — they can cooperate much more flexibly , but they do so only in small numbers , because cooperation among chimpanzees is based on intimate knowledge , one of the other .
__fi__ I &apos;m a chimpanzee and you &apos;re a chimpanzee , and I want to cooperate with you .
__fi__ I need to know you personally .
__fi__ What kind of chimpanzee are you ?
__fi__ Are you a nice chimpanzee ?
__fi__ Are you an evil chimpanzee ?
__fi__ Are you trustworthy ?
__fi__ If I don &apos;t know you , how can I cooperate with you ?
__fi__ The only animal that can combine the two abilities together and cooperate both flexibly and still do so in very large numbers is us , Homo sapiens .
__fi__ One versus one , or even 10 versus 10 , chimpanzees might be better than us .
__fi__ But , if you pit 1,000 humans against 1,000 chimpanzees , the humans will win easily , for the simple reason that a thousand chimpanzees cannot cooperate at all .
__fi__ And if you now try to cram 100,000 chimpanzees into Oxford Street , or into Wembley Stadium , or Tienanmen Square or the Vatican , you will get chaos , complete chaos .
__fi__ Just imagine Wembley Stadium with 100,000 chimpanzees .
__fi__ Complete madness .
__fi__ In contrast , humans normally gather there in tens of thousands , and what we get is not chaos , usually .
__fi__ What we get is extremely sophisticated and effective networks of cooperation .
__fi__ All the huge achievements of humankind throughout history , whether it &apos;s building the pyramids or flying to the moon , have been based not on individual abilities , but on this ability to cooperate flexibly in large numbers .
__fi__ Think even about this very talk that I &apos;m giving now : I &apos;m standing here in front of an audience of about 300 or 400 people , most of you are complete strangers to me .
__fi__ Similarly , I don &apos;t really know all the people who have organized and worked on this event .
__fi__ I don &apos;t know the pilot and the crew members of the plane that brought me over here , yesterday , to London .
__fi__ I don &apos;t know the people who invented and manufactured this microphone and these cameras , which are recording what I &apos;m saying .
__fi__ I don &apos;t know the people who wrote all the books and articles that I read in preparation for this talk .
__fi__ And I certainly don &apos;t know all the people who might be watching this talk over the Internet , somewhere in Buenos Aires or in New Delhi .
__fi__ Nevertheless , even though we don &apos;t know each other , we can work together to create this global exchange of ideas .
__fi__ This is something chimpanzees cannot do .
__fi__ They communicate , of course , but you will never catch a chimpanzee traveling to some distant chimpanzee band to give them a talk about bananas or about elephants , or anything else that might interest chimpanzees .
__fi__ Now cooperation is , of course , not always nice ; all the horrible things humans have been doing throughout history — and we have been doing some very horrible things — all those things are also based on large-scale cooperation .
__fi__ Prisons are a system of cooperation ; slaughterhouses are a system of cooperation ; concentration camps are a system of cooperation .
__fi__ Chimpanzees don &apos;t have slaughterhouses and prisons and concentration camps .
__fi__ Now suppose I &apos;ve managed to convince you perhaps that yes , we control the world because we can cooperate flexibly in large numbers .
__fi__ The next question that immediately arises in the mind of an inquisitive listener is : How , exactly , do we do it ?
__fi__ What enables us alone , of all the animals , to cooperate in such a way ?
__fi__ The answer is our imagination .
__fi__ We can cooperate flexibly with countless numbers of strangers , because we alone , of all the animals on the planet , can create and believe fictions , fictional stories .
__fi__ And as long as everybody believes in the same fiction , everybody obeys and follows the same rules , the same norms , the same values .
__fi__ All other animals use their communication system only to describe reality .
__fi__ A chimpanzee may say , &quot; &quot; Look ! There &apos;s a lion , let &apos;s run away ! &quot; &quot; Or , &quot; &quot; Look ! There &apos;s a banana tree over there ! Let &apos;s go and get bananas ! &quot; &quot; Humans , in contrast , use their language not merely to describe reality , but also to create new realities , fictional realities .
__fi__ A human can say , &quot; &quot; Look , there is a god above the clouds !
__fi__ And if you don &apos;t do what I tell you to do , when you die , God will punish you and send you to hell . &quot; &quot; And if you all believe this story that I &apos;ve invented , then you will follow the same norms and laws and values , and you can cooperate .
__fi__ This is something only humans can do .
__fi__ You can never convince a chimpanzee to give you a banana by promising him , &quot; &quot; ... after you die , you &apos;ll go to chimpanzee heaven ... &quot; &quot; ( Laughter ) &quot; &quot; ... and you &apos;ll receive lots and lots of bananas for your good deeds .
__fi__ So now give me this banana . &quot; &quot; No chimpanzee will ever believe such a story .
__fi__ Only humans believe such stories , which is why we control the world , whereas the chimpanzees are locked up in zoos and research laboratories .
__fi__ Now you may find it acceptable that yes , in the religious field , humans cooperate by believing in the same fictions .
__fi__ Millions of people come together to build a cathedral or a mosque or fight in a crusade or a jihad , because they all believe in the same stories about God and heaven and hell .
__fi__ But what I want to emphasize is that exactly the same mechanism underlies all other forms of mass-scale human cooperation , not only in the religious field .
__fi__ Take , for example , the legal field .
__fi__ Most legal systems today in the world are based on a belief in human rights .
__fi__ But what are human rights ?
__fi__ Human rights , just like God and heaven , are just a story that we &apos;ve invented .
__fi__ They are not an objective reality ; they are not some biological effect about homo sapiens .
__fi__ Take a human being , cut him open , look inside , you will find the heart , the kidneys , neurons , hormones , DNA , but you won &apos;t find any rights .
__fi__ The only place you find rights are in the stories that we have invented and spread around over the last few centuries .
__fi__ They may be very positive stories , very good stories , but they &apos;re still just fictional stories that we &apos;ve invented .
__fi__ The same is true of the political field .
__fi__ The most important factors in modern politics are states and nations .
__fi__ But what are states and nations ?
__fi__ They are not an objective reality .
__fi__ A mountain is an objective reality .
__fi__ You can see it , you can touch it , you can even smell it .
__fi__ But a nation or a state , like Israel or Iran or France or Germany , this is just a story that we &apos;ve invented and became extremely attached to .
__fi__ The same is true of the economic field .
__fi__ The most important actors today in the global economy are companies and corporations .
__fi__ Many of you today , perhaps , work for a corporation , like Google or Toyota or McDonald &apos;s .
__fi__ What exactly are these things ?
__fi__ They are what lawyers call legal fictions .
__fi__ They are stories invented and maintained by the powerful wizards we call lawyers .
__fi__ ( Laughter ) And what do corporations do all day ?
__fi__ Mostly , they try to make money .
__fi__ Yet , what is money ?
__fi__ Again , money is not an objective reality ; it has no objective value .
__fi__ Take this green piece of paper , the dollar bill .
__fi__ Look at it — it has no value .
__fi__ You cannot eat it , you cannot drink it , you cannot wear it .
__fi__ But then came along these master storytellers — the big bankers , the finance ministers , the prime ministers — and they tell us a very convincing story : &quot; &quot; Look , you see this green piece of paper ?
__fi__ It is actually worth 10 bananas . &quot; &quot; And if I believe it , and you believe it , and everybody believes it , it actually works .
__fi__ I can take this worthless piece of paper , go to the supermarket , give it to a complete stranger whom I &apos;ve never met before , and get , in exchange , real bananas which I can actually eat .
__fi__ This is something amazing .
__fi__ You could never do it with chimpanzees .
__fi__ Chimpanzees trade , of course : &quot; Yes , you give me a coconut , I &apos;ll give you a banana . &quot;
__fi__ That can work .
__fi__ But , you give me a worthless piece of paper and you except me to give you a banana ?
__fi__ No way !
__fi__ What do you think I am , a human ?
__fi__ ( Laughter ) Money , in fact , is the most successful story ever invented and told by humans , because it is the only story everybody believes .
__fi__ Not everybody believes in God , not everybody believes in human rights , not everybody believes in nationalism , but everybody believes in money , and in the dollar bill .
__fi__ Take , even , Osama Bin Laden .
__fi__ He hated American politics and American religion and American culture , but he had no objection to American dollars .
__fi__ He was quite fond of them , actually .
__fi__ ( Laughter ) To conclude , then : We humans control the world because we live in a dual reality .
__fi__ All other animals live in an objective reality .
__fi__ Their reality consists of objective entities , like rivers and trees and lions and elephants .
__fi__ We humans , we also live in an objective reality .
__fi__ In our world , too , there are rivers and trees and lions and elephants .
__fi__ But over the centuries , we have constructed on top of this objective reality a second layer of fictional reality , a reality made of fictional entities , like nations , like gods , like money , like corporations .
__fi__ And what is amazing is that as history unfolded , this fictional reality became more and more powerful so that today , the most powerful forces in the world are these fictional entities .
__fi__ Today , the very survival of rivers and trees and lions and elephants depends on the decisions and wishes of fictional entities , like the United States , like Google , like the World Bank — entities that exist only in our own imagination .
