__fi__ And every soundscape that springs from a wild habitat generates its own unique signature , one that contains incredible amounts of information , and it &apos;s some of that information I want to share with you today .
__fi__ The soundscape is made up of three basic sources .
__fi__ The first is the geophony , or the nonbiological sounds that occur in any given habitat , like wind in the trees , water in a stream , waves at the ocean shore , movement of the Earth .
__fi__ The second of these is the biophony .
__fi__ The biophony is all of the sound that &apos;s generated by organisms in a given habitat at one time and in one place .
__fi__ And the third is all of the sound that we humans generate that &apos;s called anthrophony .
__fi__ Some of it is controlled , like music or theater , but most of it is chaotic and incoherent , which some of us refer to as noise .
__fi__ There was a time when I considered wild soundscapes to be a worthless artifact .
__fi__ They were just there , but they had no significance .
__fi__ Well , I was wrong . What I learned from these encounters was that careful listening gives us incredibly valuable tools by which to evaluate the health of a habitat across the entire spectrum of life .
__fi__ When I began recording in the late &apos; 60s , the typical methods of recording were limited to the fragmented capture of individual species like birds mostly , in the beginning , but later animals like mammals and amphibians .
__fi__ To me , this was a little like trying to understand the magnificence of Beethoven &apos;s Fifth Symphony by abstracting the sound of a single violin player out of the context of the orchestra and hearing just that one part .
__fi__ Fortunately , more and more institutions are implementing the more holistic models that I and a few of my colleagues have introduced to the field of soundscape ecology .
