__fi__ ( Laughter ) Well after spending about 20 years in the recycling industry , it &apos;s become pretty clear to me that we don &apos;t necessarily leave these toddler rules behind as we develop into adults .
__fi__ And let me tell you why I have that perspective .
__fi__ Because each and every day at our recycling plants around the world we handle about one million pounds of people &apos;s discarded stuff .
__fi__ Now a million pounds a day sounds like a lot of stuff , but it &apos;s a tiny drop of the durable goods that are disposed each and every year around the world — well less than one percent .
__fi__ In fact , the United Nations estimates that there &apos;s about 85 billion pounds a year of electronics waste that gets discarded around the world each and every year — and that &apos;s one of the most rapidly growing parts of our waste stream .
__fi__ And if you throw in other durable goods like automobiles and so forth , that number well more than doubles .
__fi__ And of course , the more developed the country , the bigger these mountains .
__fi__ Now when you see these mountains , most people think of garbage .
__fi__ We see above-ground mines .
__fi__ And the reason we see mines is because there &apos;s a lot of valuable raw materials that went into making all of this stuff in the first place .
__fi__ And it &apos;s becoming increasingly important that we figure out how to extract these raw materials from these extremely complicated waste streams .
__fi__ Because as we &apos;ve heard all week at TED , the world &apos;s getting to be a smaller place with more people in it who want more and more stuff .
__fi__ And of course , they want the toys and the tools that many of us take for granted .
__fi__ And what goes into making those toys and tools that we use every single day ?
__fi__ It &apos;s mostly many types of plastics and many types of metals .
__fi__ And the metals , we typically get from ore that we mine in ever widening mines and ever deepening mines around the world .
__fi__ And the plastics , we get from oil , which we go to more remote locations and drill ever deeper wells to extract .
__fi__ And these practices have significant economic and environmental implications that we &apos;re already starting to see today .
__fi__ The good news is we are starting to recover materials from our end-of-life stuff and starting to recycle our end-of-life stuff , particularly in regions of the world like here in Europe that have recycling policies in place that require that this stuff be recycled in a responsible manner .
__fi__ Most of what &apos;s extracted from our end-of-life stuff , if it makes it to a recycler , are the metals .
__fi__ To put that in perspective — and I &apos;m using steel as a proxy here for metals , because it &apos;s the most common metal — if your stuff makes it to a recycler , probably over 90 percent of the metals are going to be recovered and reused for another purpose .
__fi__ Plastics are a whole other story : well less than 10 percent are recovered .
__fi__ In fact , it &apos;s more like five percent .
__fi__ Most of it &apos;s incinerated or landfilled .
__fi__ Now most people think that &apos;s because plastics are a throw-away material , have very little value .
__fi__ But actually , plastics are several times more valuable than steel .
__fi__ And there &apos;s more plastics produced and consumed around the world on a volume basis every year than steel .
__fi__ So why is such a plentiful and valuable material not recovered at anywhere near the rate of the less valuable material ?
__fi__ Well it &apos;s predominantly because metals are very easy to recycle from other materials and from one another .
__fi__ They have very different densities .
__fi__ They have different electrical and magnetic properties .
__fi__ And they even have different colors .
__fi__ So it &apos;s very easy for either humans or machines to separate these metals from one another and from other materials .
__fi__ Plastics have overlapping densities over a very narrow range .
__fi__ They have either identical or very similar electrical and magnetic properties .
__fi__ And any plastic can be any color , as you probably well know .
__fi__ So the traditional ways of separating materials just simply don &apos;t work for plastics .
__fi__ Another consequence of metals being so easy to recycle by humans is that a lot of our stuff from the developed world — and sadly to say , particularly from the United States , where we don &apos;t have any recycling policies in place like here in Europe — finds its way to developing countries for low-cost recycling .
__fi__ People , for as little as a dollar a day , pick through our stuff .
__fi__ They extract what they can , which is mostly the metals — circuit boards and so forth — and they leave behind mostly what they can &apos;t recover , which is , again , mostly the plastics .
__fi__ Or they burn the plastics to get to the metals in burn houses like you see here .
__fi__ And they extract the metals by hand .
__fi__ Now while this may be the low-economic-cost solution , this is certainly not the low-environmental or human health-and-safety solution .
__fi__ I call this environmental arbitrage .
__fi__ And it &apos;s not fair , it &apos;s not safe and it &apos;s not sustainable .
__fi__ Now because the plastics are so plentiful — and by the way , those other methods don &apos;t lead to the recovery of plastics , obviously — but people do try to recover the plastics .
__fi__ This is just one example .
__fi__ This is a photo I took standing on the rooftops of one of the largest slums in the world in Mumbai , India .
__fi__ They store the plastics on the roofs .
__fi__ They bring them below those roofs into small workshops like these , and people try very hard to separate the plastics , by color , by shape , by feel , by any technique they can .
